  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Establish Services for Communities (S4C) in the Central African Republic (CAR)  through Emergency Telecommunications Cluster (ETC)</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">As part of the 2019 Humanitarian Response Plan (HRP), the Emergency Telecommunications Cluster (ETC) conducted a communications and information needs assessment in the Central African Republic (CAR) in January 2019 on behalf of the larger Humanitarian Country Team (HCT). The purpose of the assessment aimed to determine whether Internally Displaced Persons (IDP) communities have access to information to identify the information of highest importance and relevance to them to identify communication channels available to IDP communities, and to identify the challenges that IDP communities face when seeking reliable, relevant and life-saving information.

Based on the findings of this assessment, the project aims to establish community information centers for affected populations, which will enable communities to access life-saving information, communicate with humanitarians and learn important life skills. The community information centers will: 

	Enable affected communities (particularly women) to access information about humanitarian assistance and humanitarian complaint mechanisms
	Serve as free-of-charge battery charging stations for mobile devices within the shelter sites
	Serve as venues providing the affected communities with training on using computers and the Internet
	Act as visibility spots, informing communities of humanitarian hotline numbers and educating them about humanitarian assistance.

Ultimately, the project will contribute to an environment of accountability to affected populations (AAP).

To ensure the functionality of community information centers&#x2019;, the project team will establish reliable telecommunications infrastructure, including a power source, voice connectivity and Internet services.</narrative>
  </description>
